WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:17.000
In the last few videos, we've talked through some very technical types of attacks.

00:17.000 --> 00:20.000
We've talked about cross-site scripting, we've talked about sequel injection,

00:20.000 --> 00:30.000
and later on, we'll even talk about buffer overflows. I want to talk about a very simple way to prevent these types of attacks,

00:30.000 --> 00:36.000
because what all of these attacks have to do with these attacks?

00:36.000 --> 00:40.000
In the last few videos, we've talked through some very technical types of attacks.

00:40.000 --> 00:44.000
We've talked about cross-site scripting, we've talked about sequel injection.

00:44.000 --> 00:48.000
Later on, we'll even talk about buffer overflows.

00:48.000 --> 00:55.000
What all of these attacks fundamentally rely on is a system that is vulnerable, and what do I mean by that?

00:55.000 --> 01:02.000
It's a system that is accepting input from a user and storing that input that it should never be accepting and storing.

01:02.000 --> 01:07.000
This is why, and remember this, drill this into your head, the root of all evil for these types of attacks,

01:07.000 --> 01:13.000
like cross-site scripting, sequel injection, buffer overflows, is that it's inadequate data validation.

01:13.000 --> 01:20.000
We're not properly validating what users input. We're not sanitizing their input, and we're not cleaning up their input.

01:20.000 --> 01:24.000
The root of all evil is inadequate data validation.

01:24.000 --> 01:32.000
So how do we fundamentally fix problems like cross-site scripting and sequel injection and buffer overflows input validation?

01:32.000 --> 01:38.000
So here's a big hint for the exam. You will very likely see very technical questions on things like cross-site scripting.

01:38.000 --> 01:43.000
The solution to how you fix these very technical types of attacks is typically very simple.

01:43.000 --> 01:50.000
Validate the user's input. If you do not allow JavaScript code to be sent, stored on the server,

01:50.000 --> 01:54.000
and then re-display to users, you prevent all of these problems from occurring.

01:54.000 --> 02:01.000
If you don't take sequel code and then send it directly to the database, you prevent sequel injection.

02:01.000 --> 02:07.000
If you don't allow input that's too large for the buffer, you don't allow buffer overflows to occur.

02:07.000 --> 02:15.000
So the simple answer you're going to look for on the exam to how you solve these very technical types of attacks is input validation.

02:15.000 --> 02:20.000
Now it might be phrased in different ways and often in more technical ways.

02:20.000 --> 02:25.000
But fundamentally, any answer that says you're sanitizing the input, you're cleaning up the input.

02:25.000 --> 02:32.000
You're somehow validating what the user provides, that's input validation, and that's the answer you should look for.

02:32.000 --> 02:37.000
And one final piece I'll talk about here. This whole section is about how do we secure web-based applications.

02:37.000 --> 02:41.000
And I'll show this diagram. I've shown a number of times now.

02:41.000 --> 02:46.000
And that is the one of the best ways of securing a system is to harden the system.

02:46.000 --> 02:51.000
Go through a well-defined set of steps, a baseline, to lock that system down.

02:51.000 --> 02:55.000
Disable unnecessary services, closed unused ports, all that sort of stuff.

02:55.000 --> 02:58.000
That's how we secure our web-based applications.

